{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d97dc77d-fb47-4085-b4f5-3cd928f66cd7","content":"Here's what I found in `my_app/views.py`:\n\n**Line 3** — `datetime.now()` — Direct static call; impossible to control in tests.\n\n### Why it's a problem\nCalling `datetime.now()` directly couples your code to the system clock. Tests can't freeze or advance time, leading to flaky assertions.\n\n### Recommended fix\nUse Django's timezone-aware `django.utils.timezone.now` and inject it or mock it:\n\n```python\nfrom django.utils import timezone\n\ndef index(request):\n    now = timezone.now()\n    return render(request, 'index.html', {'time': now})\n```\n\nThen in tests you can use [`freezegun`](https://github.com/spulec/freezegun) or `unittest.mock.patch`:\n\n```python\nfrom freezegun import freeze_time\n\n@freeze_time(\"2026-01-01\")\ndef test_index(self):\n    response = self.client.get(\"/\")\n    ...\n```\n\nThis was a small project — only **1 file / 1 occurrence** found. No other untestable statics (`date.today()`, `time.time()`, `uuid4()`, `random.*`, `os.environ`, etc.) were detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8c5d62cb-28da-4bb1-a8f0-b55b05ac0604","outputTokens":295,"requestId":"A048:34F832:1BF3A94:200A204:69FEA1DB"},"id":"5ef5b961-c218-4942-8d41-5e06f43362c2","timestamp":"2026-05-09T02:54:26.610Z","parentId":"2a7549aa-c622-4a7f-94f6-f09233388370"}
